    "faq_Y7pXfz": {
      "type": "faq",
      "blocks": {
        "question_a3Hcac": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "What should I wear to a summer day wedding as an Indian guest?",
            "text": "<p>Skip the costume drama. Choose chiffon sarees with delicate threadwork, soft brocade anarkalis, or silk kurtas in calming pastels. These Indian wedding guest outfits are breathable, photograph beautifully in daylight, and won’t leave you with regrets years later.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_CceWHU": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "Are sarees too formal for a daytime Indian wedding?",
            "text": "<p>Not at all. Sarees for Indian wedding guests are timeless. A pastel chiffon saree with subtle embroidery, paired with a plain silk blouse, is the definition of quiet luxury.<br/>Bonus: You won’t look like a reality show contestant at a billionaire’s sangeet.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_rkF3EU": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "Can I wear a lehenga to a day wedding?",
            "text": "<p>Yes — as long as it’s not weighed down with layers of net, gimmicks, or unnecessary drama. Choose lightweight lehengas with minimal embroidery in fresh colours. Think graceful, not theatrical.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_tPVewe": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "What’s trending for Indian day weddings in 2025?",
            "text": "<p>Three words: Simplicity. Silhouette. Sanity.<br/><br/>Trending right now:<br/>\t•\tSleeveless silk blouses with chiffon sarees<br/>\t•\tTraditional brocade with a soft sheen<br/>\t•\tKurta sets that don’t try too hard<br/>\t•\tPastel lehengas that let your smile shine<br/><br/>Not trending:<br/>\t•\tGimmicky drapes<br/>\t•\tLoud prints<br/>\t•\tOver-constructed fusion pieces that confuse everyone</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_giWnTe": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "Can I wear a kurta set or an anarkali as a wedding guest?",
            "text": "<p>Absolutely. A well-fitted kurta or anarkali in chanderi, silk, or organza is elegant and timeless.<br/>Pair it with a good pair of jhumkas and a confident walk — you’re good to go.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_MzfcLA": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "What’s the biggest mistake guests make when dressing for Indian weddings?",
            "text": "<p>Confusing loudness with impact. Avoid rushed, trendy pieces that don’t photograph well or age well. Loud prints, exaggerated cuts, and experimental silhouettes rarely become heirlooms — or good memories.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_qrzFVQ": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "What are the best colours to wear to a day wedding in India?",
            "text": "<p>Stick with tones that flatter you and the sun. Top choices include:<br/>\t•\tFall green<br/>\t•\tIvory, blush pink<br/>\t•\tPowder blue<br/>\t•\tSoft gold or beige<br/><br/>These look graceful and photograph beautifully in natural light.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_jKQU8d": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "Can I look stylish without looking overdressed?",
            "text": "<p>Yes — the answer is intentional elegance. You don’t need to dress like the bridal party or outshine the décor. Focus on great cuts, quality fabrics, and accessories that don’t scream for attention.<br/>A touch of gajra or a good pair of earrings does more than any shoulder feather ever could.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_g7ByjJ": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "What does Summer by Priyanka Gupta recommend for wedding guests?",
            "text": "<p>Always timeless, always graceful:<br/>\t•\tChiffon sarees with soft embroidery<br/>\t•\tSleeveless silk or raw silk blouses<br/>\t•\tTraditional brocade sarees<br/>\t•\tClassic anarkalis and well-tailored kurta sets<br/><br/>These pieces don’t chase trends — they create memories.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_KRWPwD": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "What colours should I wear for a Haldi or Mehendi ceremony?",
            "text": "<p>Haldi: Yellow is tradition — try marigold, mustard, or turmeric tones.<br/>Mehendi: Vibrant colours shine — leafy green, rani pink, orange, and peacock blue work wonderfully.<br/>Just make sure your outfit is easy to move in, especially if there’s dancing or floor seating involved.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_WwArdT": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "What should I wear to a Sikh wedding?",
            "text": "<p>Always wear a kurta set or suit with a dupatta — you’ll need it to respectfully cover your head inside the gurdwara.<br/>Avoid revealing cuts or flashy pieces. Sikh weddings are serene, and elegance goes a long way.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_tGrWcU": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "I’m not Indian. What should I wear as a guest to an Indian wedding?",
            "text": "<p>You’ll be welcomed with open arms — and probably fed second helpings.<br/><br/>You can wear:<br/>\t•\tA sari, lehenga, or kurta set (we’ll help you drape)<br/>\t•\tA fusion outfit in festive colours<br/>\t•\tA modern, elegant western dress (great for cocktails or Christian ceremonies)<br/><br/>For Haldi or Mehendi: choose happy colours like yellow, green, pink, or even orange — anything vibrant that feels celebratory.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_beDQmk": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "Can I wear a Western dress?",
            "text": "<p>Yes — especially if it’s elegant and thoughtfully styled.<br/>A deep jewel-tone midi, a pastel silk maxi, or a well-tailored dress in festive hues can fit right in. Just avoid casual fabrics or beachwear vibes.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_qbHLJe": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "Can I wear a traditional outfit from my own culture?",
            "text": "<p>Absolutely. Indian families love when guests bring their own culture to the celebration — it makes the wedding feel even more special.<br/><br/>Silk kimono? Nigerian headwrap? Hanbok? Yes, yes, and yes.<br/>Just make it festive, respectful, and joyful — you’ll be complimented all night.</p>"
          }
        },
        "question_YpXAc8": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "Is it too much to wear a lehenga?",
            "text": "<p>Nothing is too much at an Indian wedding. But at Summer, we believe that a good lehenga is one that can be worn again — at another wedding, a Diwali party, or even re-styled separately.<br/><br/>Because timeless design always gets the last word.</p>"
